merged over the question of religion in schools. James Farney and Clark Banack employ a method of process-tracing, drawing on 88 semi-structured interviews with key policy insiders. They also reference archival material documenting meetings, political speeches, and legislative debates related to government decisions around issues of religious education. Relying on the theoretical foundations of both historical institutionalism and Canadian political development, Faith, Rights, and Choice presents a new analytic framework to help make sense of the policy divergence witnessed across Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada education.  aCatholic school board.  aOntario education.  aOntario.  apolicy change.  apolicy history.  aprovincial policy and politics.  aprovincial variation.  apublic policy.  areligious education.  areligious school.1 aBanack, Clark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831107973670 cprintz978148754580240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754911440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487549114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487549114/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles